# Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) Implementation Project

## Overview

During my internship at Linamar, I supported and led the implementation of Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) across more than 250+ users as part of an organization-wide identity and access management (IAM) security initiative.

The goal of the project was to strengthen account security by reducing the risk of credential-based attacks and ensuring users transitioned from weak or single-factor authentication methods to secure MFA solutions.

---

## Objectives

* Identify users without MFA enabled across the organization.
* Enforce and support MFA adoption for all users.
* Strengthen identity and access management (IAM) security posture.
* Reduce risk of account compromise and unauthorized access.
* Provide user guidance and support during MFA onboarding.

---

## Role & Responsibilities

### User Identification & Assessment

I acted as the first point of contact for MFA rollout and was responsible for identifying users who had not yet enabled MFA on their accounts.

This involved:

* Reviewing user authentication status
* Identifying non-compliant accounts
* Coordinating with users across departments
* Tracking adoption progress during rollout

---

### MFA Deployment & User Enablement

I supported the implementation of MFA across 250+ users by guiding them through setup and activation of secure authentication methods.

Users were assisted in configuring:

* Microsoft Authenticator (primary method)
* Hardware-based authentication (YubiKey) for users preferring physical security keys
* Secure recovery and backup authentication options

---

### Documentation & User Support

To ensure smooth adoption, I created and shared step-by-step documentation for MFA setup, including:

* Microsoft Authenticator setup guide
* YubiKey configuration instructions
* Troubleshooting common enrollment issues
* Best practices for account security

I also provided direct support to users experiencing issues during setup to ensure successful enrollment.

---

